# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: matlab-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Although MATLAB is intended primarily for numeric computing, an optional toolbox uses the MuPAD symbolic engine allowing access to symbolic computing abilities.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] An additional package, Simulink, adds graphical multi-domain simulation and model-based design for dynamic and embedded systems.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] As of 2020, MATLAB has more than four million users worldwide.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] They come from various backgrounds of engineering, science, and economics.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] As of 2017, more than 5000 global colleges and universities use MATLAB to support instruction and research.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB was invented by mathematician and computer programmer Cleve Moler.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The idea for MATLAB was based on his 1960s PhD thesis.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Moler became a math professor at the University of New Mexico and started developing MATLAB for his students as a hobby.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] He developed MATLAB's initial linear algebra programming in 1967 with his one-time thesis advisor, George Forsythe.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] This was followed by Fortran code for linear equations in 1971.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Before version 1.0, MATLAB "was not a programming language; it was a simple interactive matrix calculator.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] There were no programs, no toolboxes, no graphics.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The first early version of MATLAB was completed in the late 1970s.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The software was disclosed to the public for the first time in February 1979 at the Naval Postgraduate School in California.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Early versions of MATLAB were simple matrix calculators with 71 pre-built functions.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] At the time, MATLAB was distributed for free to universities.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Moler would leave copies at universities he visited and the software developed a strong following in the math departments of university campuses.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] They decided to reprogram MATLAB in C and market it for the IBM desktops that were replacing mainframe computers at the time.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] John Little and programmer Steve Bangert re-programmed MATLAB in C, created the MATLAB programming language, and developed features for toolboxes.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB was first released as a commercial product in 1984 at the Automatic Control Conference in Las Vegas.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MathWorks, Inc. was founded to develop the software and the MATLAB programming language was released.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The first MATLAB sale was the following year, when Nick Trefethen from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology bought ten copies.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] By the end of the 1980s, several hundred copies of MATLAB had been sold to universities for student use.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The software was popularized largely thanks to toolboxes created by experts in various fields for performing specialized mathematical tasks.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Many of the toolboxes were developed as a result of Stanford students that used MATLAB in academia, then brought the software with them to the private sector.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Over time, MATLAB was re-written for early operating systems created by Digital Equipment Corporation, VAX, Sun Microsystems, and for Unix PCs.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The first MATLAB compiler was developed by Stephen C.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] In 2000, MathWorks added a Fortran-based library for linear algebra in MATLAB 6, replacing the software's original LINPACK and EISPACK subroutines that were in C.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB's Parallel Computing Toolbox was released at the 2004 Supercomputing Conference and support for graphics processing units (GPUs) was added to it in 2010.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Some especially large changes to the software were made with version 8 in 2012.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The user interface was reworked and Simulink's functionality was expanded.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] By 2016, MATLAB had introduced several technical and user interface improvements, including the MATLAB Live Editor notebook, and other features.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] For a complete list of changes of both MATLAB an official toolboxes, check MATLAB previous releases.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The MATLAB application is built around the MATLAB programming language.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Common usage of the MATLAB application involves using the "Command Window" as an interactive mathematical shell or executing text files containing MATLAB code.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] An example of a "Hello, world!" program exists in MATLAB.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Variables are defined using the assignment operator, `=`.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB is a weakly typed programming language because types are implicitly converted.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] It is an inferred typed language because variables can be assigned without declaring their type, except if they are to be treated as symbolic objects, and that their type can change.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Values can come from constants, from computation involving values of other variables, or from the output of a function.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] A simple array is defined using the colon syntax: *initial*`:`*increment*`:`*terminator*.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] defines a variable named `array` (or assigns a new value to an existing variable with the name `array`) which is an array consisting of the values 1, 3, 5, 7, and 9.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] That is, the array starts at 1 (the *initial* value), increments with each step from the previous value by 2 (the *increment* value), and stops once it reaches (or is about to exceed) 9 (the *terminator* value).
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The *increment* value can actually be left out of this syntax (along with one of the colons), to use a default value of 1.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] assigns to the variable named `ari` an array with the values 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5, since the default value of 1 is used as the increment.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Indexing is one-based, which is the usual convention for matrices in mathematics, unlike zero-based indexing commonly used in other programming languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Matrices can be defined by separating the elements of a row with blank space or comma and using a semicolon to separate the rows.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The list of elements should be surrounded by square brackets `[]`.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Parentheses `()` are used to access elements and subarrays (they are also used to denote a function argument list).
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Sets of indices can be specified by expressions such as `2:4`, which evaluates to `[2, 3, 4]`.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] A square identity matrix of size *n* can be generated using the function `eye`, and matrices of any size with zeros or ones can be generated with the functions `zeros` and `ones`, respectively.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Most functions accept arrays as input and operate element-wise on each element.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] For example, `mod(2*J,n)` will multiply every element in *J* by 2, and then reduce each element modulo *n*.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB does include standard `for` and `while` loops, but (as in other similar applications such as APL and R), using the vectorized notation is encouraged and is often faster to execute.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Since all variables in MATLAB are arrays, a more adequate name is "structure array", where each element of the array has the same field names.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] In addition, MATLAB supports dynamic field names (field look-ups by name, field manipulations, etc.).
[src:matlab-language/matlab] When creating a MATLAB function, the name of the file should match the name of the first function in the file.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Valid function names begin with an alphabetic character, and can contain letters, numbers, or underscores.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Variables and functions are case sensitive.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB supports elements of lambda calculus by introducing function handles, or function references, which are implemented either in .m files or anonymous/nested functions.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB supports object-oriented programming including classes, inheritance, virtual dispatch, packages, pass-by-value semantics, and pass-by-reference semantics.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] However, the syntax and calling conventions are significantly different from other languages.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB has value classes and reference classes, depending on whether the class has *handle* as a super-class (for reference classes) or not (for value classes).
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Method call behavior is different between value and reference classes.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] can alter any member of *object* only if *object* is an instance of a reference class, otherwise value class methods must return a new instance if it needs to modify the object.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB has tightly integrated graph-plotting features.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] For example, the function *plot* can be used to produce a graph from two vectors *x* and *y*.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB supports developing graphical user interface (GUI) applications.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] UIs can be generated either programmatically or using visual design environments such as *GUIDE* and *App Designer*.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MATLAB can call functions and subroutines written in the programming languages C or Fortran.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] A wrapper function is created allowing MATLAB data types to be passed and returned.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] MEX files (MATLAB executables) are the dynamically loadable object files created by compiling such functions.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Since 2014 increasing two-way interfacing with Python was being added.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Libraries written in Perl, Java, ActiveX or .NET can be directly called from MATLAB, and many MATLAB libraries (for example XML or SQL support) are implemented as wrappers around Java or ActiveX libraries.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Calling MATLAB from Java is more complicated, but can be done with a MATLAB toolbox which is sold separately by MathWorks, or using an undocumented mechanism called JMI (Java-to-MATLAB Interface), (which should not be confused with the unrelated Java Metadata Interface that is also called JMI).
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Official MATLAB API for Java was added in 2016.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] As alternatives to the MuPAD based Symbolic Math Toolbox available from MathWorks, MATLAB can be connected to Maple or Mathematica.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] Libraries also exist to import and export MathML.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] In 2020, MATLAB withdrew services from two Chinese universities as a result of US sanctions.
[src:matlab-language/matlab] The universities said this will be responded to by increased use of open-source alternatives and by developing domestic alternatives.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **matrix** (pl.: **matrices**) is a rectangular array of numbers or other mathematical objects with elements or entries arranged in rows and columns, usually satisfying certain properties of addition and multiplication.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, ${\begin{bmatrix}1&9&-13\\20&5&-6\end{bmatrix}}$ denotes a matrix with two rows and three columns.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This is often referred to as a "two-by-three matrix", a 2 × 3 matrix, or a matrix of dimension 2 × 3.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In linear algebra, matrices are used as linear maps.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In geometry, matrices are used for geometric transformations (for example rotations) and coordinate changes.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In numerical analysis, many computational problems are solved by reducing them to a matrix computation, and this often involves computing with matrices of huge dimensions.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are used in most areas of mathematics and scientific fields, either directly, or through their use in geometry and numerical analysis.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers (or other mathematical objects), called the "entries" of the matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are subject to standard operations such as addition and multiplication.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Most commonly, a matrix over a field F is a rectangular array of elements of ⁠ F ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **real matrix** and a **complex matrix** are matrices whose entries are respectively real numbers or complex numbers.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] More general types of entries are discussed below.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The numbers (or other objects) in the matrix are called its *entries* or its *elements*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The horizontal and vertical lines of entries in a matrix are respectively called *rows* and *columns*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The size of a matrix is defined by the number of rows and columns it contains.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] There is no limit to the number of rows and columns that a matrix (in the usual sense) can have as long as they are positive integers.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with m rows and n columns is called an m × n matrix, or m-by-n matrix, where m and n are called its **dimensions**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the matrix ${\mathbf {A} }$ above is a 3 × 2 matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices with a single row are called *row matrices* or *row vectors*, and those with a single column are called *column matrices* or *column vectors*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with the same number of rows and columns is called a *square matrix*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with an infinite number of rows or columns (or both) is called an *infinite matrix*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In some contexts, such as computer algebra programs, it is useful to consider a matrix with no rows or no columns, called an *empty matrix*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The specifics of symbolic matrix notation vary widely, with some prevailing trends.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are usually symbolized using upper-case letters (such as ${\mathbf {A} }$ in the examples above), while the corresponding lower-case letters, with two subscript indices (e.g., ⁠ $a_{11}$ ⁠, or ⁠ $a_{1,1}$ ⁠), represent the entries.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In addition to using upper-case letters to symbolize matrices, many authors use a special typographical style, commonly boldface roman (non-italic), to further distinguish matrices from other mathematical objects.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An alternative notation involves the use of a double-underline with the variable name, with or without boldface style, as in ⁠ ${\underline {\underline {A}}}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entry in the *i*th row and *j*th column of a matrix **A** is sometimes referred to as the ${i,j}$ or $(i,j)$ entry of the matrix, and commonly denoted by $a_{i,j}$ or ⁠ $a_{ij}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Alternative notations for that entry are ${\mathbf {A} [i,j]}$ and ⁠ $\mathbf {A} _{i,j}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Sometimes, the entries of a matrix can be defined by a formula such as ⁠ $a_{i,j}=f(i,j)$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the matrix above is defined as ${\mathbf {A} }=[i-j]$ or ⁠ $\mathbf {A} =((i-j))$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If matrix size is m × n, the above-mentioned formula $f(i,j)$ is valid for any $i=1,\dots ,m$ and any ⁠ $j=1,\dots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This can be specified separately or indicated using m × n as a subscript.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some programming languages utilize doubly subscripted arrays (or arrays of arrays) to represent an {m-by-n matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some programming languages start the numbering of array indexes at zero, in which case the entries of an m × n matrix are indexed by $0\leq i\leq m-1$ and ⁠ $0\leq j\leq n-1$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This article follows the more common convention in mathematical writing where enumeration starts from 1.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of all m-by-n real matrices is often denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(m,n)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{m\times n}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of all m × n matrices over another field, or over a ring *R*, is similarly denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(m,n,R)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{m\times n}(R)$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *m* = *n*, such as in the case of square matrices, one does not repeat the dimension: ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(n,R)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Often, ⁠ M ⁠, or ⁠ $\operatorname {Mat}$ ⁠, is used in place of ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Several basic operations can be applied to matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some, such as *transposition* and *submatrix* do not depend on the nature of the entries.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Others, such as *matrix addition*, *scalar multiplication*, *matrix multiplication*, and *row operations* involve operations on matrix entries and therefore require that matrix entries are numbers or belong to a field or a ring.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In this section, it is supposed that matrix entries belong to a fixed ring, which is typically a field of numbers.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix addition and subtraction require matrices of a consistent size, and are calculated entrywise.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Familiar properties of numbers extend to these operations on matrices: for example, addition is commutative, that is, the matrix sum does not depend on the order of the summands: **A** + **B** = **B** + **A**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The transpose is compatible with addition and scalar multiplication, as expressed by (*c***A**)T = *c*(**A**T) and (**A** + **B**)T = **A**T + **B**T.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix multiplication satisfies the rules (**AB**)**C** = **A**(**BC**) (associativity), and (**A** + **B**)**C** = **AC** + **BC** as well as **C**(**A** + **B**) = **CA** + **CB** (left and right distributivity), whenever the size of the matrices is such that the various products are defined.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The product **AB** may be defined without **BA** being defined, namely if **A** and **B** are m × n and n × k matrices, respectively, and *m* ≠ *k*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In other words, matrix multiplication is not commutative, in marked contrast to (rational, real, or complex) numbers, whose product is independent of the order of the factors.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Besides the ordinary matrix multiplication just described, other less frequently used operations on matrices that can be considered forms of multiplication also exist, such as the Hadamard product and the Kronecker product.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] They arise in solving matrix equations such as the Sylvester equation.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] These operations are used in several ways, including solving linear equations and finding matrix inverses with Gauss elimination and Gauss–Jordan elimination, respectively.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **submatrix** of a matrix is a matrix obtained by deleting any collection of rows or columns or both.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The minors and cofactors of a matrix are found by computing the determinant of certain submatrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **principal submatrix** is a square submatrix obtained by removing certain rows and columns.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The definition varies from author to author.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] According to some authors, a principal submatrix is a submatrix in which the set of row indices that remain is the same as the set of column indices that remain.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Other authors define a principal submatrix as one in which the first k rows and columns, for some number k, are the ones that remain; this type of submatrix has also been called a **leading principal submatrix**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices can be used to compactly write and work with multiple linear equations, that is, systems of linear equations.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Using matrices, this can be solved more compactly than would be possible by writing out all the equations separately.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *n* = *m* and the equations are independent, then this can be done by writing $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {A} ^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ where **A**−1 is the inverse matrix of **A**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **A** has no inverse, solutions—if any—can be found using its generalized inverse.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices and matrix multiplication reveal their essential features when related to *linear transformations*, also known as *linear maps*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The matrix **A** is said to represent the linear map f, and **A** is called the *transformation matrix* of f.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the 2 × 2 matrix $\mathbf {A} ={\begin{bmatrix}a&c\\b&d\end{bmatrix}}$ can be viewed as the transform of the unit square into a parallelogram with vertices at (0, 0), (*a*, *b*), (*a* + *c*, *b* + *d*), and (*c*, *d*).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] These vectors define the vertices of the unit square.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The following table shows several 2 × 2 real matrices with the associated linear maps of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The blue original is mapped to the green grid and shapes.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The origin (0, 0) is marked with a black point.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The last equality follows from the above-mentioned associativity of matrix multiplication.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The rank of a matrix **A** is the maximum number of linearly independent row vectors of the matrix, which is the same as the maximum number of linearly independent column vectors.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Equivalently it is the dimension of the image of the linear map represented by **A**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The rank–nullity theorem states that the dimension of the kernel of a matrix plus the rank equals the number of columns of the matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix is a matrix with the same number of rows and columns.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An n-by-n matrix is known as a square matrix of order n.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Any two square matrices of the same order can be added and multiplied.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entries aii form the main diagonal of a square matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] They lie on the imaginary line running from the top left corner to the bottom right corner of the matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Square matrices of a given dimension form a noncommutative ring, which is one of the most common examples of a noncommutative ring.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If all entries of **A** below the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called an *upper triangular matrix*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Similarly, if all entries of **A** above the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called a *lower triangular matrix*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If all entries outside the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called a diagonal matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is called an identity matrix because multiplication with it leaves a matrix unchanged: ${\mathbf {AI}}_{n}={\mathbf {I}}_{m}{\mathbf {A}}={\mathbf {A}}$ for any m-by-n matrix **A**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A scalar multiple of an identity matrix is called a *scalar* matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix **A** that is equal to its transpose, that is, **A** = **A**T, is a symmetric matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If instead, **A** is equal to the negative of its transpose, that is, **A** = −**A**T, then **A** is a skew-symmetric matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In complex matrices, symmetry is often replaced by the concept of Hermitian matrices, which satisfies **A**∗ = **A**, where the star or asterisk denotes the conjugate transpose of the matrix, that is, the transpose of the complex conjugate of **A**.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] By the spectral theorem, real symmetric matrices and complex Hermitian matrices have an eigenbasis; that is, every vector is expressible as a linear combination of eigenvectors.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In both cases, all eigenvalues are real.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This theorem can be generalized to infinite-dimensional situations related to matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix **A** is called *invertible* or *non-singular* if there exists a matrix **B** such that ${\mathbf {AB}}={\mathbf {BA}}={\mathbf {I}}_{n},$ where **I***n* is the n × n identity matrix with 1 for each entry on the main diagonal and 0 elsewhere.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **B** exists, it is unique and is called the *inverse matrix* of **A**, denoted **A**−1.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are many algorithms for testing whether a square matrix is invertible, and, if it is, computing its inverse.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] One of the oldest, which is still in common use is Gaussian elimination.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A symmetric real matrix **A** is called *positive-definite* if the associated quadratic form $f({\mathbf {x}})={\mathbf {x}}^{\rm {T}}{\mathbf {Ax}}$ has a positive value for every nonzero vector **x** in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *f*(**x**) yields only negative values then **A** is *negative-definite*; if f does produce both negative and positive values then **A** is *indefinite*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A symmetric matrix is positive-definite if and only if all its eigenvalues are positive, that is, the matrix is positive-semidefinite and it is invertible.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The table at the right shows two possibilities for 2-by-2 matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix are simply the entries along the diagonal, and so in these examples, the eigenvalues can be read directly from the matrices themselves.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The first matrix has two eigenvalues that are both positive, while the second has one that is positive and another that is negative.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In the case of complex matrices, the same terminology and results apply, with *symmetric matrix*, *quadratic form*, *bilinear form*, and *transpose* **x**T replaced respectively by Hermitian matrix, Hermitian form, sesquilinear form, and conjugate transpose **x**H.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An *orthogonal matrix* is a square matrix with real entries whose columns and rows are orthogonal unit vectors (that is, orthonormal vectors).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Equivalently, a matrix **A** is orthogonal if its transpose is equal to its inverse: $\mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }=\mathbf {A} ^{-1},\,$ which entails $\mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {A} =\mathbf {A} \mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }=\mathbf {I} _{n},$ where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size n.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of any orthogonal matrix is either +1 or −1.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A *special orthogonal matrix* is an orthogonal matrix with determinant +1.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The identity matrices have determinant 1 and are pure rotations by an angle zero.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The complex analog of an orthogonal matrix is a unitary matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The trace, tr(**A**) of a square matrix **A** is the sum of its diagonal entries.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The *determinant* of a square matrix **A** (denoted det(**A**) or |**A**|) is a number encoding certain properties of the matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is nonzero.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Its absolute value equals the area (in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠) or volume (in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ ⁠) of the image of the unit square (or cube), while its sign corresponds to the orientation of the corresponding linear map: the determinant is positive if and only if the orientation is preserved.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of 2 × 2 matrices is given by $\det {\begin{bmatrix}a&b\\c&d\end{bmatrix}}=ad-bc.$ The determinant of 3 × 3 matrices involves six terms (rule of Sarrus).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The more lengthy Leibniz formula generalizes these two formulae to all dimensions.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Interchanging two rows or two columns affects the determinant by multiplying it by −1.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Using these operations, any matrix can be transformed to a lower (or upper) triangular matrix, and for such matrices, the determinant equals the product of the entries on the main diagonal; this provides a method to calculate the determinant of any matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Finally, the Laplace expansion expresses the determinant in terms of minors, that is, determinants of smaller matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This expansion can be used for a recursive definition of determinants (taking as starting case the determinant of a 1 × 1 matrix, which is its unique entry, or even the determinant of a 0 × 0 matrix, which is 1), that can be seen to be equivalent to the Leibniz formula.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Determinants can be used to solve linear systems using Cramer's rule, where the division of the determinants of two related square matrices equates to the value of each of the system's variables.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A number ${\textstyle \lambda }$ and a nonzero vector **v** satisfying $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ are called an *eigenvalue* and an *eigenvector* of **A**, respectively.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Therefore the polynomial equation *p***A**(*λ*) = 0 has at most n different solutions, that is, eigenvalues of the matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] They may be complex even if the entries of **A** are real.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] According to the Cayley–Hamilton theorem, *p***A**(**A**) = **0**, that is, the result of substituting the matrix itself into its characteristic polynomial yields the zero matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix calculations can be often performed with different techniques.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Many problems can be solved by both direct algorithms and iterative approaches.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the eigenvectors of a square matrix can be obtained by finding a sequence of vectors **x***n* converging to an eigenvector when n tends to infinity.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] To choose the most appropriate algorithm for each specific problem, it is important to determine both the effectiveness and precision of all the available algorithms.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The domain studying these matters is called numerical linear algebra.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] As with other numerical situations, two main aspects are the complexity of algorithms and their numerical stability.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Determining the complexity of an algorithm means finding upper bounds or estimates of how many elementary operations such as additions and multiplications of scalars are necessary to perform some algorithm, for example, multiplication of matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Calculating the matrix product of two n-by-n matrices using the definition given above needs *n*3 multiplications, since for any of the *n*2 entries of the product, n multiplications are necessary.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The Strassen algorithm outperforms this "naive" algorithm; it needs only *n*2.807 multiplications.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Theoretically faster but impractical matrix multiplication algorithms have been developed, as have speedups to this problem using parallel algorithms or distributed computation systems such as MapReduce.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In many practical situations, additional information about the matrices involved is known.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An important case concerns sparse matrices, that is, matrices whose entries are mostly zero.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are specifically adapted algorithms for, say, solving linear systems **Ax** = **b** for sparse matrices **A**, such as the conjugate gradient method.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An algorithm is, roughly speaking, numerically stable if little deviations in the input values do not lead to big deviations in the result.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, one can calculate the inverse of a matrix by computing its adjugate matrix: ${\mathbf {A}}^{-1}=\operatorname {adj} ({\mathbf {A}})/\det({\mathbf {A}}).$ However, this may lead to significant rounding errors if the determinant of the matrix is very small.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The norm of a matrix can be used to capture the conditioning of linear algebraic problems, such as computing a matrix's inverse.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are several methods to render matrices into a more easily accessible form.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] They are generally referred to as *matrix decomposition* or *matrix factorization* techniques.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] These techniques are of interest because they can make computations easier.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The LU decomposition factors matrices as a product of lower (**L**) and an upper triangular matrices (**U**).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Once this decomposition is calculated, linear systems can be solved more efficiently by a simple technique called forward and back substitution.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Likewise, inverses of triangular matrices are algorithmically easier to calculate.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The *Gaussian elimination* is a similar algorithm; it transforms any matrix to row echelon form.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Both methods proceed by multiplying the matrix by suitable elementary matrices, which correspond to permuting rows or columns and adding multiples of one row to another row.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Singular value decomposition (SVD) expresses any matrix **A** as a product **UDV**∗, where **U** and **V** are unitary matrices and **D** is a diagonal matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The eigendecomposition or *diagonalization* expresses **A** as a product **VDV**−1, where **D** is a diagonal matrix and **V** is a suitable invertible matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **A** can be written in this form, it is called diagonalizable.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This can be used to compute the matrix exponential *e***A**, a need frequently arising in solving linear differential equations, matrix logarithms and square roots of matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] To avoid numerically ill-conditioned situations, further algorithms such as the Schur decomposition can be employed.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices can be generalized in different ways.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Abstract algebra uses matrices with entries in more general fields or even rings, while linear algebra codifies properties of matrices in the notion of linear maps.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is possible to consider matrices with infinitely many columns and rows.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Another extension is tensors, which can be seen as higher-dimensional arrays of numbers, as opposed to vectors, which can often be realized as sequences of numbers, while matrices are rectangular or two-dimensional arrays of numbers.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices, subject to certain requirements tend to form groups known as matrix groups.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Similarly under certain conditions matrices form rings known as matrix rings.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Though the product of matrices is not in general commutative, certain matrices form fields sometimes called matrix fields.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The objects of this category are natural numbers, representing the dimensions of the matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This article focuses on matrices whose entries are real or complex numbers.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, matrices can be considered with much more general types of entries than real or complex numbers.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] As a first step of generalization, any field, that is, a set where addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations are defined and well-behaved, may be used instead of ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠, for example rational numbers or finite fields.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, coding theory makes use of matrices over finite fields.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Wherever eigenvalues are considered, as these are roots of a polynomial, they may exist only in a larger field than that of the entries of the matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For instance, they may be complex in the case of a matrix with real entries.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The possibility to reinterpret the entries of a matrix as elements of a larger field (for example, to view a real matrix as a complex matrix whose entries happen to be all real) then allows considering each square matrix to possess a full set of eigenvalues.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Alternatively one can consider only matrices with entries in an algebraically closed field, such as ⁠ $\mathbb {C} ,$ ⁠ from the outset.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices whose entries are polynomials, and more generally, matrices with entries in a ring R are widely used in mathematics.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Rings are a more general notion than fields in that a division operation need not exist.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The very same addition and multiplication operations of matrices extend to this setting, too.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set M(*n*, *R*) (also denoted M*n*(R)) of all square n-by-n matrices over R is a ring called matrix ring, isomorphic to the endomorphism ring of the left R-module Rn.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] If the ring R is commutative, that is, its multiplication is commutative, then the ring M(*n*, *R*) is also an associative algebra over *R*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of square matrices over a commutative ring R can still be defined using the Leibniz formula; such a matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is invertible in R, generalizing the situation over a field F, where every nonzero element is invertible.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices over superrings are called supermatrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices do not always have all their entries in the same ring – or even in any ring at all.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] One special but common case is block matrices, which may be considered as matrices whose entries themselves are matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entries need not be square matrices, and thus need not be members of any ring; but in order to multiply them, their sizes must fulfill certain conditions: each pair of submatrices that are multiplied in forming the overall product must have compatible sizes.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Linear maps $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ are equivalent to m-by-n matrices, as described above.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The matrix depends on the choice of the bases: different choices of bases give rise to different, but equivalent matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Many of the above concrete notions can be reinterpreted in this light, for example, the transpose matrix **A**T describes the transpose of the linear map given by **A**, concerning the dual bases.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] These properties can be restated more naturally: the category of matrices with entries in a field k with multiplication as composition is equivalent to the category of finite-dimensional vector spaces and linear maps over this field.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] More generally, the set of m × n matrices can be used to represent the R-linear maps between the free modules Rm and Rn for an arbitrary ring R with unity.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] When *n* = *m* composition of these maps is possible, and this gives rise to the matrix ring of n × n matrices representing the endomorphism ring of Rn.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A group is a mathematical structure consisting of a set of objects together with a binary operation, that is, an operation combining any two objects to a third, subject to certain requirements.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A group in which the objects are invertible ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices and the group operation is matrix multiplication is called a *matrix group* of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every such matrix group is a subgroup of (that is, a smaller group contained within) the group of *all* invertible ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices, the general linear group of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Any property of square matrices that is preserved under matrix products and inverses can be used to define a matrix group.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of all ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices whose determinant is 1 form a group called the special linear group of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of orthogonal matrices, determined by the condition ${\mathbf {M}}^{\rm {T}}{\mathbf {M}}={\mathbf {I}},$ form the orthogonal group.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every orthogonal matrix has determinant 1 or −1.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Orthogonal matrices with determinant 1 form a group called the *special orthogonal group*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every finite group is isomorphic to a matrix group, as one can see by considering the regular representation of the symmetric group.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] General groups can be studied using matrix groups, which are comparatively well understood, using representation theory.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is also possible to consider matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The basic operations introduced above are defined the same way in this case.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix multiplication, however, and all operations stemming therefrom are only meaningful when restricted to certain matrices, since the sum featuring in the above definition of the matrix product will contain an infinity of summands.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An easy way to circumvent this issue is to restrict to *finitary matrices* all of whose rows (or columns) contain only finitely many nonzero terms.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] As in the finite case (see above), where matrices describe linear maps, infinite matrices can be used to describe operators on Hilbert spaces, where convergence and continuity questions arise.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, the explicit point of view of matrices tends to obfuscate the matter, and the abstract and more powerful tools of functional analysis are used instead, by relating matrices to linear maps (as in the finite case above), but imposing additional convergence and continuity constraints.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] An *empty matrix* is a matrix in which the number of rows or columns (or both) is zero.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Empty matrices can be a useful base case for certain recursive constructions, and can help to deal with maps involving the zero vector space.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, if **A** is a 3 × 0 matrix and **B** is a 0 × 3 matrix, then **AB** is the 3 × 3 zero matrix corresponding to the null map from a 3-dimensional space V to itself, while **BA** is a 0 × 0 matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] There is no common notation for empty matrices, but most computer algebra systems allow creating and computing with them.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of the 0 × 0 matrix is conventionally defined to be 1, consistent with the empty product occurring in the Leibniz formula for the determinant.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] This value is also needed for consistency with the 2 × 2 case of the Desnanot–Jacobi identity relating determinants to the determinants of smaller matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] A semiring is similar to a ring, but elements need not have additive inverses, therefore one cannot do subtraction freely there.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The definition of addition and multiplication of matrices with entries in a ring applies to matrices with entries in a semiring without modification.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices of fixed size with entries in a semiring form a commutative monoid $\operatorname {Mat} (m,n;R)$ under addition.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Square matrices of fixed size with entries in a semiring form a semiring $\operatorname {Mat} (n;R)$ under addition and multiplication.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of an n × n square matrix M with entries in a commutative semiring R cannot be defined in general because the definition would involve additive inverses of semiring elements.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] where the sums are taken over even permutations and odd permutations, respectively.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices and their multiplication can be defined with entries objects of a category equipped with a "tensor product" similar to multiplication in a ring, having coproducts similar to addition in a ring, in that the former is distributive over the latter.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, the multiplication thus defined may be only associative in a sense weaker than usual.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] These are part of a bigger structure called the *bicategory of matrices*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] The complete description of the above summary for interested readers follows.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] In general, the bicategory of matrices need not be a strict 2-category.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the composition of 1-morphisms may not be associative in the usual strict sense, but only up to coherent isomorphism.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] There are numerous applications of matrices, both in mathematics and other sciences.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Some of them merely take advantage of the compact representation of a set of numbers in a matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, text mining and automated thesaurus compilation makes use of document-term matrices such as tf-idf to track frequencies of certain words in several documents.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Complex numbers can be represented by particular real 2-by-2 matrices via $a+ib\leftrightarrow {\begin{bmatrix}a&-b\\b&a\end{bmatrix}},$ under which addition and multiplication of complex numbers and matrices correspond to each other.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, 2-by-2 rotation matrices represent the multiplication with some complex number of absolute value 1, as above.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] A similar interpretation is possible for quaternions and Clifford algebras in general.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] In game theory and economics, the payoff matrix encodes the payoff for two players, depending on which out of a given (finite) set of strategies the players choose.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The expected outcome of the game, when both players play mixed strategies, is obtained by multiplying this matrix on both sides by vectors representing the strategies.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The minimax theorem central to game theory is closely related to the duality theory of linear programs, which are often formulated in terms of matrix-vector products.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Early encryption techniques such as the Hill cipher also used matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] However, due to the linear nature of matrices, these codes are comparatively easy to break.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices over a polynomial ring are important in the study of control theory.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Chemistry makes use of matrices in various ways, particularly since the use of quantum theory to discuss molecular bonding and spectroscopy.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Examples are the overlap matrix and the Fock matrix used in solving the Roothaan equations to obtain the molecular orbitals of the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The adjacency matrix of a finite graph is a basic notion of graph theory.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] It records which vertices of the graph are connected by an edge.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices containing just two different values (1 and 0 meaning for example "yes" and "no", respectively) are called logical matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The distance (or cost) matrix contains information about the distances of the edges.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] These concepts can be applied to websites connected by hyperlinks, or cities connected by roads etc., in which case (unless the connection network is extremely dense) the matrices tend to be sparse, that is, contain few nonzero entries.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Therefore, specifically tailored matrix algorithms can be used in network theory.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] It encodes information about the local growth behavior of the function: given a critical point **x** = (*x*1, ..., *xn*), that is, a point where the first partial derivatives $\partial f/\partial x_{i}$ of f vanish, the function has a local minimum if the Hessian matrix is positive definite.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Quadratic programming can be used to find global minima or maxima of quadratic functions closely related to the ones attached to matrices (see above).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Another matrix frequently used in geometrical situations is the Jacobi matrix of a differentiable map ⁠ $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Partial differential equations can be classified by considering the matrix of coefficients of the highest-order differential operators of the equation.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] For elliptic partial differential equations this matrix is positive definite, which has a decisive influence on the set of possible solutions of the equation in question.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The finite element method is an important numerical method to solve partial differential equations, widely applied in simulating complex physical systems.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] It attempts to approximate the solution to some equation by piecewise linear functions, where the pieces are chosen concerning a sufficiently fine grid, which in turn can be recast as a matrix equation.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Stochastic matrices are square matrices whose rows are probability vectors, that is, whose entries are non-negative and sum up to one.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Stochastic matrices are used to define Markov chains with finitely many states.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] A row of the stochastic matrix gives the probability distribution for the next position of some particle currently in the state that corresponds to the row.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Properties of the Markov chain—like absorbing states, that is, states that any particle attains eventually—can be read off the eigenvectors of the transition matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Statistics also makes use of matrices in many different forms.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Descriptive statistics is concerned with describing data sets, which can often be represented as data matrices, which may then be subjected to dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The covariance matrix encodes the mutual variance of several random variables.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Random matrices are matrices whose entries are random numbers, subject to suitable probability distributions, such as matrix normal distribution.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Beyond probability theory, they are applied in domains ranging from number theory to physics.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The first model of quantum mechanics (Heisenberg, 1925) used infinite-dimensional matrices to define the operators that took over the role of variables like position, momentum and energy from classical physics.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] (This is sometimes referred to as matrix mechanics.) Matrices, both finite and infinite-dimensional, have since been employed for many purposes in quantum mechanics.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] One particular example is the density matrix, a tool used in calculating the probabilities of the outcomes of measurements performed on physical systems.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Linear transformations and the associated symmetries play a key role in modern physics.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, elementary particles in quantum field theory are classified as representations of the Lorentz group of special relativity and, more specifically, by their behavior under the spin group.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Concrete representations involving the Pauli matrices and more general gamma matrices are an integral part of the physical description of fermions, which behave as spinors.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Cabibbo–Kobayashi–Maskawa matrix, in turn, expresses the fact that the basic quark states that are important for weak interactions are not the same as, but linearly related to the basic quark states that define particles with specific and distinct masses.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The linear combination is given by a matrix known as the S-matrix, which encodes all information about the possible interactions between particles.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] A general application of matrices in physics is the description of linearly coupled harmonic systems.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The equations of motion of such systems can be described in matrix form, with a mass matrix multiplying a generalized velocity to give the kinetic term, and a force matrix multiplying a displacement vector to characterize the interactions.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The best way to obtain solutions is to determine the system's eigenvectors, its normal modes, by diagonalizing the matrix equation.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Techniques like this are crucial when it comes to the internal dynamics of molecules: the internal vibrations of systems consisting of mutually bound component atoms.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] They are also needed for describing mechanical vibrations, and oscillations in electrical circuits.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Geometrical optics provides further matrix applications.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] In this approximative theory, the wave nature of light is neglected.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The result is a model in which light rays are indeed geometrical rays.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] There are two kinds of matrices, viz. a *refraction matrix* describing the refraction at a lens surface, and a *translation matrix*, describing the translation of the plane of reference to the next refracting surface, where another refraction matrix applies.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The optical system, consisting of a combination of lenses and reflective elements, is simply described by the matrix resulting from the product of the components' matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Jones calculus models the polarization of a light source as a $2\times 2$ vector, and the effects of optical filters on this polarization vector as a matrix.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices have a long history of application in solving linear equations but they were known as arrays until the 1800s.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Chinese text *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art* written in the 10th–2nd century BCE is the first example of the use of array methods to solve simultaneous equations.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] In 1545 Italian mathematician Gerolamo Cardano introduced the method to Europe when he published *Ars Magna*.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Japanese mathematician Seki used the same array methods to solve simultaneous equations in 1683.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Dutch mathematicianJan de Witt represented transformations using arrays in his 1659 book *Elements of Curves* (1659).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Between 1700 and 1710 Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz publicized the use of arrays for recording information or solutions and experimented with over 50 different systems of arrays.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Arthur Cayley published a treatise on geometric transformations using matrices that were not rotated versions of the coefficients being investigated as had previously been done.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Instead, he defined operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division as transformations of those matrices and showed the associative and distributive properties held.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Cayley investigated and demonstrated the non-commutative property of matrix multiplication as well as the commutative property of matrix addition.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Early matrix theory had limited the use of arrays almost exclusively to determinants and Cayley's abstract matrix operations were revolutionary.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] He was instrumental in proposing a matrix concept independent of equation systems.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] In 1858, Cayley published his *A memoir on the theory of matrices* in which he proposed and demonstrated the Cayley–Hamilton theorem.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The English mathematician Cuthbert Edmund Cullis was the first to use modern bracket notation for matrices in 1913 and he simultaneously demonstrated the first significant use of the notation **A** = [*a**i*,*j*] to represent a matrix where *a**i*,*j* refers to the ith row and the jth column.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The modern study of determinants sprang from several sources.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Number-theoretical problems led Gauss to relate coefficients of quadratic forms, that is, expressions such as *x*2 + *xy* − 2*y*2, and linear maps in three dimensions to matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Eisenstein further developed these notions, including the remark that, in modern parlance, matrix products are non-commutative.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] He also showed, in 1829, that the eigenvalues of symmetric matrices are real.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Jacobi studied "functional determinants"—later called Jacobi determinants by Sylvester—which can be used to describe geometric transformations at a local (or infinitesimal) level, see above.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Kronecker's *Vorlesungen über die Theorie der Determinanten* and Weierstrass's *Zur Determinantentheorie*, both published in 1903, first treated determinants axiomatically, as opposed to previous more concrete approaches such as the mentioned formula of Cauchy.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] At that point, determinants were firmly established.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Many theorems were first established for small matrices only, for example, the Cayley–Hamilton theorem was proved for 2 × 2 matrices by Cayley in the aforementioned memoir, and by Hamilton for 4 × 4 matrices.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Frobenius, working on bilinear forms, generalized the theorem to all dimensions (1898).
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Also at the end of the 19th century, the Gauss–Jordan elimination (generalizing a special case now known as Gauss elimination) was established by Wilhelm Jordan.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] In the early 20th century, matrices attained a central role in linear algebra, partially due to their use in the classification of the hypercomplex number systems of the previous century.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The inception of matrix mechanics by Heisenberg, Born and Jordan led to studying matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Later, von Neumann carried out the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics, by further developing functional analytic notions such as linear operators on Hilbert spaces, which, very roughly speaking, correspond to Euclidean space, but with an infinity of independent directions.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] The word has been used in unusual ways by at least two authors of historical importance.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Bertrand Russell and Alfred North Whitehead in their *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913) use the word "matrix" in the context of their axiom of reducibility.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, a function Φ(*x*, *y*) of two variables x and y can be reduced to a *collection* of functions of a single variable, such as y, by "considering" the function for all possible values of "individuals" ai substituted in place of a variable x.
[src:matlab-language/matrix-mathematics-p02] Alfred Tarski in his 1941 *Introduction to Logic* used the word "matrix" synonymously with the notion of truth table as used in mathematical logic.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis finds application in all fields of engineering and the physical sciences, and in the 21st century also the life and social sciences like economics, medicine, business and even the arts.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Current growth in computing power has enabled the use of more complex numerical analysis, providing detailed and realistic mathematical models in science and engineering.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Before modern computers, numerical methods often relied on hand interpolation formulas, using data from large printed tables.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Since the mid-20th century, computers calculate the required functions instead, but many of the same formulas continue to be used in software algorithms.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The numerical point of view goes back to the earliest mathematical writings.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] A tablet from the Yale Babylonian Collection (YBC 7289), gives a sexagesimal numerical approximation of the square root of 2, the length of the diagonal in a unit square.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis continues this long tradition: rather than giving exact symbolic answers translated into digits and applicable only to real-world measurements, approximate solutions within specified error bounds are used.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis predates the invention of modern computers by many centuries.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Linear interpolation was already in use more than 2000 years ago.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Many great mathematicians of the past were preoccupied by numerical analysis, as is obvious from the names of important algorithms like Newton's method, Lagrange interpolation polynomial, Gaussian elimination, or Euler's method.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The origins of modern numerical analysis are often linked to a 1947 paper by John von Neumann and Herman Goldstine, but others consider modern numerical analysis to go back to work by E.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] To facilitate computations by hand, large books were produced with formulas and tables of data such as interpolation points and function coefficients.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Using these tables, often calculated out to 16 decimal places or more for some functions, one could look up values to plug into the formulas given and achieve very good numerical estimates of some functions.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The canonical work in the field is the NIST publication edited by Abramowitz and Stegun, a 1000-plus page book of a very large number of commonly used formulas and functions and their values at many points.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The function values are no longer very useful when a computer is available, but the large listing of formulas can still be very handy.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The mechanical calculator was also developed as a tool for hand computation.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] These calculators evolved into electronic computers in the 1940s, and it was then found that these computers were also useful for administrative purposes.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] But the invention of the computer also influenced the field of numerical analysis, since now longer and more complicated calculations could be done.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The Leslie Fox Prize for Numerical Analysis was initiated in 1985 by the Institute of Mathematics and its Applications.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Direct methods compute the solution to a problem in a finite number of steps.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] These methods would give the precise answer if they were performed in infinite precision arithmetic.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Examples include Gaussian elimination, the QR factorization method for solving systems of linear equations, and the simplex method of linear programming.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] In practice, finite precision is used and the result is an approximation of the true solution (assuming stability).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] In contrast to direct methods, iterative methods are not expected to terminate in a finite number of steps, even if infinite precision were possible.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Starting from an initial guess, iterative methods form successive approximations that converge to the exact solution only in the limit.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] A convergence test, often involving the residual, is specified in order to decide when a sufficiently accurate solution has (hopefully) been found.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Even using infinite precision arithmetic these methods would not reach the solution within a finite number of steps (in general).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Examples include Newton's method, the bisection method, and Jacobi iteration.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] In computational matrix algebra, iterative methods are generally needed for large problems.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods are more common than direct methods in numerical analysis.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Some methods are direct in principle but are usually used as though they were not, e.g.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] GMRES and the conjugate gradient method.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For these methods the number of steps needed to obtain the exact solution is so large that an approximation is accepted in the same manner as for an iterative method.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For the iterative method, apply the bisection method to *f*(*x*) = 3*x*3 − 24.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] From this table it can be concluded that the solution is between 1.875 and 2.0625.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The algorithm might return any number in that range with an error less than 0.2.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Ill-conditioned problem: Take the function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Evaluating *f*(*x*) near *x* = 1 is an ill-conditioned problem.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Well-conditioned problem: By contrast, evaluating the same function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1) near *x* = 10 is a well-conditioned problem.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Furthermore, continuous problems must sometimes be replaced by a discrete problem whose solution is known to approximate that of the continuous problem; this process is called 'discretization'.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For example, the solution of a differential equation is a function.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] This function must be represented by a finite amount of data, for instance by its value at a finite number of points at its domain, even though this domain is a continuum.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The study of errors forms an important part of numerical analysis.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] There are several ways in which error can be introduced in the solution of the problem.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Round-off errors arise because it is impossible to represent all real numbers exactly on a machine with finite memory (which is what all practical digital computers are).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Truncation errors are committed when an iterative method is terminated or a mathematical procedure is approximated and the approximate solution differs from the exact solution.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Similarly, discretization induces a discretization error because the solution of the discrete problem does not coincide with the solution of the continuous problem.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] In the example above to compute the solution of $3x^{3}+4=28$ , after ten iterations, the calculated root is roughly 1.99.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Therefore, the truncation error is roughly 0.01.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Once an error is generated, it propagates through the calculation.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For example, the operation + on a computer is inexact.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] A calculation of the type ⁠ $a+b+c+d+e$ ⁠ is even more inexact.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] A truncation error is created when a mathematical procedure is approximated.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] To integrate a function exactly, an infinite sum of regions must be found, but numerically only a finite sum of regions can be found, and hence the approximation of the exact solution.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Similarly, to differentiate a function, the differential element approaches zero, but numerically only a nonzero value of the differential element can be chosen.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] An algorithm is called *numerically stable* if an error, whatever its cause, does not grow to be much larger during the calculation.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] This happens if the problem is *well-conditioned*, meaning that the solution changes by only a small amount if the problem data are changed by a small amount.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] To the contrary, if a problem is 'ill-conditioned', then any small error in the data will grow to be a large error.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Both the original problem and the algorithm used to solve that problem can be well-conditioned or ill-conditioned, and any combination is possible.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] So an algorithm that solves a well-conditioned problem may be either numerically stable or numerically unstable.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] An art of numerical analysis is to find a stable algorithm for solving a well-posed mathematical problem.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis includes many sub-disciplines.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] One of the simplest problems is the evaluation of a function at a given point.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The most straightforward approach, of just plugging in the number in the formula is sometimes not very efficient.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For polynomials, a better approach is using the Horner scheme, since it reduces the necessary number of multiplications and additions.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Generally, it is important to estimate and control round-off errors arising from the use of floating-point arithmetic.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Interpolation solves the following problem: given the value of some unknown function at a number of points, what value does that function have at some other point between the given points?
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Extrapolation is very similar to interpolation, except that now the value of the unknown function at a point which is outside the given points must be found.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Regression is also similar, but it takes into account that the data are imprecise.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Given some points, and a measurement of the value of some function at these points (with an error), the unknown function can be found.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The least squares-method is one way to achieve this.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Another fundamental problem is computing the solution of some given equation.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Two cases are commonly distinguished, depending on whether the equation is linear or not.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For instance, the equation $2x+5=3$ is linear while $2x^{2}+5=3$ is not.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Much effort has been put in the development of methods for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Standard direct methods, i.e., methods that use some matrix decomposition are Gaussian elimination, LU decomposition, Cholesky decomposition for symmetric (or hermitian) and positive-definite matrix, and QR decomposition for non-square matrices.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods such as the Jacobi method, Gauss–Seidel method, successive over-relaxation and conjugate gradient method are usually preferred for large systems.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] General iterative methods can be developed using a matrix splitting.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Root-finding algorithms are used to solve nonlinear equations (they are so named since a root of a function is an argument for which the function yields zero).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] If the function is differentiable and the derivative is known, then Newton's method is a popular choice.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Linearization is another technique for solving nonlinear equations.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Several important problems can be phrased in terms of eigenvalue decompositions or singular value decompositions.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For instance, the spectral image compression algorithm is based on the singular value decomposition.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The corresponding tool in statistics is called principal component analysis.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Optimization problems ask for the point at which a given function is maximized (or minimized).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Often, the point also has to satisfy some constraints.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The field of optimization is further split in several subfields, depending on the form of the objective function and the constraint.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] For instance, linear programming deals with the case that both the objective function and the constraints are linear.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] A famous method in linear programming is the simplex method.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The method of Lagrange multipliers can be used to reduce optimization problems with constraints to unconstrained optimization problems.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Numerical integration, in some instances also known as numerical quadrature, asks for the value of a definite integral.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Popular methods use one of the Newton–Cotes formulas (like the midpoint rule or Simpson's rule) or Gaussian quadrature.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] These methods rely on a "divide and conquer" strategy, whereby an integral on a relatively large set is broken down into integrals on smaller sets.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] In higher dimensions, where these methods become prohibitively expensive in terms of computational effort, one may use Monte Carlo or quasi-Monte Carlo methods (see Monte Carlo integration), or, in modestly large dimensions, the method of sparse grids.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis is also concerned with computing (in an approximate way) the solution of differential equations, both ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Partial differential equations are solved by first discretizing the equation, bringing it into a finite-dimensional subspace.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] This can be done by a finite element method, a finite difference method, or (particularly in engineering) a finite volume method.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The theoretical justification of these methods often involves theorems from functional analysis.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] This reduces the problem to the solution of an algebraic equation.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Since the late twentieth century, most algorithms are implemented in a variety of programming languages.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The Netlib repository contains various collections of software routines for numerical problems, mostly in Fortran and C.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Commercial products implementing many different numerical algorithms include the IMSL and NAG libraries; a free-software alternative is the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Over the years the Royal Statistical Society published numerous algorithms in its *Applied Statistics* (code for these "AS" functions is here); ACM similarly, in its *Transactions on Mathematical Software* ("TOMS" code is here).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] The Naval Surface Warfare Center several times published its *Library of Mathematics Subroutines* (code here).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] There are several popular numerical computing applications such as MATLAB, TK Solver, S-PLUS, and IDL as well as free and open-source alternatives such as FreeMat, Scilab, GNU Octave (similar to Matlab), and IT++ (a C++ library).
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] There are also programming languages such as R (similar to S-PLUS), Julia, and Python with libraries such as NumPy, SciPy and SymPy.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Performance varies widely: while vector and matrix operations are usually fast, scalar loops may vary in speed by more than an order of magnitude.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Many computer algebra systems such as Mathematica also benefit from the availability of arbitrary-precision arithmetic which can provide more accurate results.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Also, any spreadsheet software can be used to solve simple problems relating to numerical analysis.
[src:matlab-language/numerical-analysis] Excel, for example, has hundreds of available functions, including for matrices, which may be used in conjunction with its built in "solver".
[src:matlab-language/simulink] MathWorks and other third-party hardware and software products can be used with Simulink.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] For example, Stateflow extends Simulink with a design environment for developing state machines and flow charts.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Simscape is an add-on product that extends Simulink with support for physical modeling.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Developed by MathWorks, it enables the modeling and simulation of multidomain physical systems by connecting physical components whose interactions represent domains such as electrical, mechanical, thermal, and fluid systems.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Simscape models can be combined with standard Simulink block diagrams, allowing the simulation of systems that couple physical dynamics with control algorithms and signal-based components.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Coupled with another of their products, Simulink can automatically generate C source code for real-time implementation of systems.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] As the efficiency and flexibility of the code improves, this is becoming more widely adopted for production systems, in addition to being a tool for embedded system design work because of its flexibility and capacity for quick iteration.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Embedded Coder creates code efficient enough for use in embedded systems.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Simulink Real-Time (formerly known as xPC Target), together with x86-based real-time systems, is an environment for simulating and testing Simulink and Stateflow models in real-time on the physical system.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Another MathWorks product also supports specific embedded targets.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] When used with other generic products, Simulink and Stateflow can automatically generate synthesizable VHDL and Verilog.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Simulink Verification and Validation enables systematic verification and validation of models through modeling style checking, requirements traceability and model coverage analysis.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] Simulink Design Verifier uses formal methods to identify design errors like integer overflow, division by zero and dead logic, and generates test case scenarios for model checking within the Simulink environment.
[src:matlab-language/simulink] SimEvents is used to add a library of graphical building blocks for modeling queuing systems to the Simulink environment, and to add an event-based simulation engine to the time-based simulation engine in Simulink.
